A6.
 The claim is that 
\begin_inset Formula $P(n)=1^{2}+2^{2}+\ldots+n^{2}=\frac{1}{6}n(n+1)(2n+1)$
\end_inset

.
 We prove this by induction.
 The base case is 
\begin_inset Formula $1^{2}=P(1)=\frac{1}{6}1(2)(3)$
\end_inset

, which is true.
 We now assume for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k)$
\end_inset

 is true, and try to prove 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k+1)$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k)=1^{2}+2^{2}+\ldots+k^{2}$
\end_inset

, we may obtain the next term by adding 
\begin_inset Formula $(k+1)^{2}=k^{2}+2k+1$
\end_inset

.
 By the induction hypothesis, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k)=\frac{k^{3}}{3}+\frac{k^{2}}{2}+\frac{k}{6}$
\end_inset

, and adding the next term, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{k^{3}}{3}+\frac{k^{2}}{2}+\frac{k}{6}+k^{2}+2k+1=\frac{k^{3}}{3}+\frac{3k^{2}}{2}+\frac{13k}{6}+1=\frac{1}{6}(k+1)((k+1)+1)(2(k+1)+1)$
\end_inset

, which is precisely 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k+1)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, with the base case and induction hypothesis, we have proved 
\begin_inset Formula $P(n)\ \forall n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

